WEBVTT

00:00:24.100 --> 00:01:24.900
[Transcript missing]

00:01:25.900 --> 00:04:48.600
[Transcript missing]

00:04:49.190 --> 00:04:51.700
We do certainly get
asked the question a lot,

00:04:51.700 --> 00:04:54.920
what is Apple doing building servers?

00:04:55.030 --> 00:05:00.790
And we absolutely passionately believe
that you can't deliver a great user

00:05:00.790 --> 00:05:05.180
experience on the desktop if you don't
have a great server backing it up.

00:05:05.330 --> 00:05:10.450
There are areas where Apple can
truly understand how to optimize

00:05:10.450 --> 00:05:14.990
to meet the needs of Mac users in
areas where competitive servers will

00:05:14.990 --> 00:05:19.890
just never have that same degree of
attention to detail or polish or focus.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:22.500
And we really believe
the mission at Apple,

00:05:22.570 --> 00:05:24.520
hopefully you've heard time
and time again this week,

00:05:24.620 --> 00:05:27.240
is to build the best
possible personal computer.

00:05:27.300 --> 00:05:30.960
And in the 21st century and
certainly in the Mac OS X era,

00:05:31.250 --> 00:05:35.050
that requires having an
incredibly strong server platform.

00:05:36.710 --> 00:05:38.360
So where are we going?

00:05:38.420 --> 00:05:43.040
Well, Apple Share IP for many, many,
many years has been an

00:05:43.140 --> 00:05:45.200
unbelievably great product for us.

00:05:45.280 --> 00:05:49.460
It's been the number one server in the
education market pretty much forever.

00:05:49.610 --> 00:05:55.510
It focuses on incredible ease of use with
great general purpose services from file,

00:05:55.790 --> 00:06:01.540
print, web, mail services now with the
current Apple Share IP product.

00:06:01.600 --> 00:06:05.550
With Mac OS X, we're going to have an
incredibly powerful platform.

00:06:05.760 --> 00:06:10.600
As you saw, hopefully,
in the hardware keynote Tuesday morning,

00:06:10.680 --> 00:06:13.420
Mac OS X,
from an infrastructure perspective,

00:06:13.460 --> 00:06:16.100
is capable of some
incredibly great things.

00:06:16.140 --> 00:06:18.690
We're going to have an
incredibly great file system,

00:06:18.750 --> 00:06:23.500
very modern network environment,
and as was hinted in the keynote,

00:06:23.500 --> 00:06:27.590
an enablement of
symmetric multiprocessing.

00:06:27.880 --> 00:06:31.760
All of these capabilities,
when you add it to the wealth of

00:06:31.840 --> 00:06:36.080
services that Apple Share provides,
leads us with an incredibly

00:06:36.190 --> 00:06:40.000
strong platform that is powerful,
robust, scalable,

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:42.700
and is easy to administer and manage.

00:06:42.750 --> 00:06:45.970
Also add on top of that the
innovative new capabilities

00:06:46.150 --> 00:06:48.080
that Mac OS X server provides.

00:06:48.120 --> 00:06:51.330
Netbooting,
the easiest way to get a network,

00:06:51.470 --> 00:06:56.140
say a classroom in a lab,
set up with almost zero administration.

00:06:56.240 --> 00:06:57.680
QuickTime streaming.

00:06:57.770 --> 00:07:01.080
QuickTime is transforming how
people communicate over the web.

00:07:01.140 --> 00:07:03.880
You need a powerful engine,
and we've delivered QuickTime streaming

00:07:04.270 --> 00:07:06.720
with the Mac OS X server product.

00:07:06.770 --> 00:07:10.910
And then you take all of that
with the context of open source.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:15.410
The fact that the Darwin layer,
we ship the source code to the very

00:07:15.410 --> 00:07:20.000
foundation of the operating system,
and it allows and enables certain

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:23.650
opportunities to enhance the system,
for you to take it in directions

00:07:23.750 --> 00:07:27.520
that maybe we haven't had
the chance to prioritize.

00:07:27.520 --> 00:07:30.540
And it makes for a much more open
and easy to work environment for

00:07:30.540 --> 00:07:32.520
certainly the developer community.

00:07:32.610 --> 00:07:36.250
You add all of that together,
and you have what we believe,

00:07:36.250 --> 00:07:39.850
and we're very excited about it,
is just an incredible,

00:07:40.010 --> 00:07:43.310
the best ever server that
Apple has ever produced.

00:07:44.010 --> 00:07:46.780
So let me just spend a couple
minutes talking about some of the

00:07:47.170 --> 00:07:50.900
history and some of the lineage
behind our current servers.

00:07:50.900 --> 00:07:55.650
And I'll focus on maybe
just two key areas,

00:07:55.980 --> 00:07:58.900
one in K12 and then one
very close to Apple.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:03.900
When Mac OS X Server was
introduced last March,

00:08:03.900 --> 00:08:06.900
there's a number of very
powerful capabilities,

00:08:06.900 --> 00:08:11.660
but one that was incredibly exciting,
very bleeding edge in terms of

00:08:11.700 --> 00:08:14.640
a new technology introduction,
was NetBoot.

00:08:14.870 --> 00:08:20.780
And we consciously picked a number
of test sites that we would be able

00:08:20.780 --> 00:08:23.900
to evaluate and test the technology.

00:08:23.900 --> 00:08:29.900
One of those was a K12 school district,
Hacienda de la Puente.

00:08:29.900 --> 00:08:36.290
And the benefits of being able to
take a server and configure it with a

00:08:36.420 --> 00:08:40.000
version of the Mac OS operating system
that had the right set of extensions,

00:08:40.050 --> 00:08:41.900
the right set of preferences,
the right applications,

00:08:41.900 --> 00:08:47.350
and literally just walk in with an iMac,
connect up a network connection,

00:08:47.350 --> 00:08:50.800
hold down the N key,
and that iMac would boot across

00:08:50.800 --> 00:08:52.900
the network off of that server.

00:08:52.900 --> 00:08:54.090
It's a very interesting technology.

00:08:54.520 --> 00:08:56.400
and others have been involved in this.

00:08:56.470 --> 00:08:57.390
Thank you.

00:09:24.400 --> 00:09:28.720
I think it's important to note that
the average service time for a school

00:09:28.880 --> 00:09:31.130
district is about two and a half days.

00:09:31.480 --> 00:09:34.500
It really has transformed the way that
school district can deliver content.

00:09:34.500 --> 00:09:36.990
Students are free to roam from
machine to machine to machine.

00:09:37.170 --> 00:09:38.670
Their work environment is always there.

00:09:38.670 --> 00:09:41.460
From an administration perspective,
they are able to keep their network

00:09:41.620 --> 00:09:43.100
up-to-date with minimal investment.

00:09:43.480 --> 00:09:48.360
It's been a highlight in terms of how
the future of technology can really

00:09:48.360 --> 00:09:53.400
change the way that people teach
and learn using computers as a tool.

00:09:54.570 --> 00:09:58.020
We've seen just incredible
interest around the world

00:09:58.380 --> 00:10:00.400
in the NetBoot technology.

00:10:00.400 --> 00:10:03.680
It's actually expanded well
beyond the K-12 market,

00:10:03.700 --> 00:10:06.650
even though that was our
initial primary focus.

00:10:06.820 --> 00:10:13.040
Another really amazing capability
with Mac OS X Server in terms of its

00:10:13.040 --> 00:10:19.160
robustness and the WebObjects application
server solution for which there are 18

00:10:19.160 --> 00:10:23.400
tracks here at the conference this week,
is just some of the incredible things you

00:10:23.490 --> 00:10:28.500
can do in terms of delivering web-based
services in concert with all the other

00:10:28.620 --> 00:10:31.440
technologies that the server provides.

00:10:31.510 --> 00:10:34.980
A couple interesting little
anecdotes about the power of

00:10:34.980 --> 00:10:37.420
Mac OS X Server in that environment.

00:10:37.480 --> 00:10:42.450
The Apple Store is one of the
leading e-commerce sites in the web,

00:10:42.720 --> 00:10:47.940
a pan market,
not just the computer technology market.

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:49.840
It is incredibly reliable.

00:10:50.040 --> 00:10:55.230
We basically, on an annualized rate,
realize about a billion dollars worth of

00:10:55.230 --> 00:10:58.420
revenue that is sold through that store,
and that is running

00:10:58.420 --> 00:11:00.780
completely on Mac OS X Server.

00:11:00.830 --> 00:11:01.460
It's an incredible service.

00:11:01.460 --> 00:11:04.130
It's an amazing thing to put
the trust of that much revenue

00:11:04.320 --> 00:11:07.560
in the hands of technology,
but we believe incredibly

00:11:08.160 --> 00:11:11.460
strongly that you have to,
these words have been used before,

00:11:11.460 --> 00:11:12.310
eat your own dog food.

00:11:12.470 --> 00:11:14.700
We use Mac OS X Server for the store.

00:11:14.700 --> 00:11:18.460
We use it to deploy a number
of the iTools solutions.

00:11:18.460 --> 00:11:20.030
We're using it for internal networks.

00:11:20.070 --> 00:11:24.460
And it's been an absolutely
amazing technology,

00:11:24.460 --> 00:11:26.610
and we're investing very,
very heavily in it.

00:11:26.780 --> 00:11:29.960
So let's walk through
the basic architecture.

00:11:30.330 --> 00:11:31.460
Hopefully this is now in order.

00:11:31.460 --> 00:11:35.670
This is an old, boring slide,
the definitive architecture

00:11:35.670 --> 00:11:37.220
roadmap of Mac OS X.

00:11:37.240 --> 00:11:40.740
Where we have the Darwin layer,
it's the operating system plumbing,

00:11:40.880 --> 00:11:43.450
strong graphics architecture,
a variety of application

00:11:43.490 --> 00:11:46.220
programming models,
and obviously the user interface.

00:11:46.220 --> 00:11:48.800
Well, how does the server fit into this?

00:11:48.920 --> 00:11:53.420
How do we map the key technologies
and the architectures and the layers

00:11:53.500 --> 00:11:56.220
that a server platform would provide?

00:11:56.220 --> 00:11:59.830
Well, take that whole Mac OS X picture
that you saw previously,

00:11:59.830 --> 00:12:01.460
and that's the
Mac OS X layer at the bottom.

00:12:01.470 --> 00:12:04.770
bottom of our server services roadmap.

00:12:05.150 --> 00:12:10.180
The important message is that our
server offerings start with the

00:12:10.190 --> 00:12:13.290
desktop product and then we add to it.

00:12:13.880 --> 00:12:18.060
We have a number of services
that I'll talk to in a moment,

00:12:18.060 --> 00:12:24.050
but there's two key bands below
and above our individual services,

00:12:24.050 --> 00:12:27.170
and that's a common directory
architecture and a common

00:12:27.170 --> 00:12:29.280
administration model.

00:12:29.740 --> 00:12:34.890
From the services perspective,
File and Print remains the primary

00:12:34.890 --> 00:12:39.700
services that a workgroup network
expects to be great and work well,

00:12:39.740 --> 00:12:42.700
especially in a Mac-oriented environment.

00:12:42.720 --> 00:12:47.130
A wealth and portfolio
of Internet services from

00:12:47.140 --> 00:12:49.700
Web through Mail and others.

00:12:49.760 --> 00:12:53.650
Comprehensive network services
and network solutions.

00:12:53.850 --> 00:12:55.700
Desktop Management Services.

00:12:55.700 --> 00:13:00.670
Desktop management allows a K-12
school administrator to create all of

00:13:00.720 --> 00:13:06.700
the policies in order to effectively
run a lab of student-driven machines.

00:13:06.700 --> 00:13:08.700
Are they allowed to access CD-ROMs?

00:13:08.700 --> 00:13:11.700
What preferences should be
managed on their behalf?

00:13:11.700 --> 00:13:14.700
Which preferences are they
allowed to manage themselves?

00:13:14.700 --> 00:13:18.070
And as I mentioned,
a comprehensive administration

00:13:18.070 --> 00:13:21.550
architecture so that we have the
ease of use and the simplicity

00:13:21.830 --> 00:13:23.700
of managing a diverse system.

00:13:23.750 --> 00:13:26.590
out of server services.

00:13:27.630 --> 00:13:32.060
So that's a very high level
perspective on our approach,

00:13:32.140 --> 00:13:33.210
our architecture.

00:13:33.260 --> 00:13:36.180
I'd like to invite on stage Greg Burns.

00:13:36.230 --> 00:13:40.340
He will talk about the server
solutions and the internet,

00:13:40.510 --> 00:13:42.490
and it's all yours.

00:13:44.360 --> 00:13:45.800
Thanks, Ken.

00:13:45.800 --> 00:13:45.800
Hi.

00:13:50.270 --> 00:13:54.340
I'm going to talk to you a bit about what
we're doing with additional services on

00:13:54.340 --> 00:13:56.800
top of the Mac OS X operating system.

00:13:56.890 --> 00:13:58.730
But before we get into that,
I want to say one more

00:13:58.730 --> 00:14:01.630
thing about Mac OS X,
the operating system itself.

00:14:01.700 --> 00:14:04.630
And you've all seen this diagram now,
I think, several times.

00:14:04.640 --> 00:14:06.560
It has Darwin down at the bottom.

00:14:06.660 --> 00:14:11.510
And hopefully many of you have heard
that Darwin is based in part on FreeBSD.

00:14:11.670 --> 00:14:14.780
And FreeBSD is not a newcomer
to the operating system world,

00:14:14.780 --> 00:14:19.980
and there's a lot of experience built
into FreeBSD running as a server.

00:14:19.980 --> 00:14:22.130
Has anybody here ever heard of Yahoo?

00:14:22.410 --> 00:14:22.860
Everybody?

00:14:22.860 --> 00:14:25.040
You should all be raising your hands.

00:14:25.150 --> 00:14:26.470
How about Hotmail?

00:14:26.740 --> 00:14:28.580
Probably heard of that as well,
Microsoft's Hotmail.

00:14:28.640 --> 00:14:31.460
Both of these are networks
that run on FreeBSD.

00:14:31.680 --> 00:14:35.960
So FreeBSD has a good pedigree
as a server operating system,

00:14:35.980 --> 00:14:39.220
and as part of the core of Mac OS X,
it provides a good foundation

00:14:39.220 --> 00:14:40.640
for providing a server.

00:14:40.690 --> 00:14:42.620
And as Ken said,
we're not a big iron company,

00:14:42.680 --> 00:14:45.740
but for our customers,
there is a strong foundation

00:14:45.740 --> 00:14:47.950
there for building services.

00:14:48.550 --> 00:14:50.980
So in Mac OS X Server,
we are providing some

00:14:50.980 --> 00:14:54.630
additional capabilities on top
of the core operating system.

00:14:54.720 --> 00:14:57.400
The first one is the
Directory Services and the

00:14:57.400 --> 00:14:59.150
Directory Architecture.

00:14:59.370 --> 00:15:04.290
And the goal here is that we want to
have a common directory that underlies

00:15:04.350 --> 00:15:08.230
all of the services and applications
using the network in Mac OS X.

00:15:08.330 --> 00:15:11.020
And we do this in two parts:
through an API that any

00:15:11.170 --> 00:15:14.050
application can use,
and this allows any service,

00:15:14.130 --> 00:15:16.690
any application, whether it be on the
client or the server,

00:15:16.780 --> 00:15:19.200
to access network resources.

00:15:19.260 --> 00:15:22.000
And because we recognize,
even though we provide a

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:24.530
directory with Mac OS X,
we recognize there are other

00:15:24.530 --> 00:15:27.500
directories in the world,
and perhaps you want to access NDS or

00:15:27.500 --> 00:15:29.600
Kerberos or some other directory.

00:15:29.760 --> 00:15:34.150
So this API provides for the
ability to access other directories.

00:15:34.280 --> 00:15:38.320
And in addition to accessing
information in directories,

00:15:38.320 --> 00:15:40.920
you also want to be able to figure
out whether or not somebody is

00:15:40.920 --> 00:15:42.620
authorized to use resources.

00:15:42.760 --> 00:15:45.660
John Smith may be in a directory,
but you also want to know if the

00:15:45.660 --> 00:15:48.490
client is in fact John Smith and
give him authorization to

00:15:48.490 --> 00:15:49.820
access certain resources.

00:15:49.970 --> 00:15:52.950
So the directory APIs include
a central authentication

00:15:52.950 --> 00:15:54.740
authority to provide for that.

00:15:54.930 --> 00:15:59.000
And together with the network information
and the central authentication authority,

00:15:59.060 --> 00:16:03.580
you can manage users
centrally in your network.

00:16:03.670 --> 00:16:05.790
And so how does it fit together?

00:16:07.520 --> 00:16:10.100
Well, the key piece here is that
green band in the middle,

00:16:10.110 --> 00:16:12.100
the Directory Access API.

00:16:12.140 --> 00:16:16.260
This exists both on the
Mac OS X desktop and on the server side.

00:16:16.320 --> 00:16:18.850
And our software,
as well as your solutions,

00:16:18.980 --> 00:16:19.880
can sit on top of this.

00:16:20.030 --> 00:16:21.360
This is a public API.

00:16:21.600 --> 00:16:25.000
We have extensive documentation for it.

00:16:25.040 --> 00:16:28.210
And it's very easy to use,
very easy to get access to any

00:16:28.320 --> 00:16:30.500
directory service through this.

00:16:30.520 --> 00:16:31.740
And underneath there,
you'll see that there

00:16:31.740 --> 00:16:32.500
are several plug-ins.

00:16:32.500 --> 00:16:34.500
There's an open plug-in architecture.

00:16:34.660 --> 00:16:36.660
And we use that ourselves.

00:16:36.870 --> 00:16:37.500
This is key.

00:16:37.500 --> 00:16:39.500
We use it ourselves
for accessing NetInfo.

00:16:39.500 --> 00:16:41.050
So we're eating our own dog food here.

00:16:41.050 --> 00:16:43.430
And all of the accesses to NetInfo,
our directory service,

00:16:43.430 --> 00:16:45.480
are done through this
plug-in architecture.

00:16:45.500 --> 00:16:47.500
We also provide LDAP, as well.

00:16:47.500 --> 00:16:52.680
But in addition, if you have a directory,
you can plug in there, as well.

00:16:52.960 --> 00:16:55.140
The API, as I said,
it exists on the desktop

00:16:55.140 --> 00:16:56.170
as well as the server.

00:16:56.490 --> 00:16:59.000
It's utilized by all of our services.

00:16:59.060 --> 00:17:01.730
In our current Mac OS 9 product,
Apple Share IP,

00:17:01.890 --> 00:17:06.170
we have Directory Services in there,
but they weren't universally

00:17:06.170 --> 00:17:09.360
utilized by all of our services,
and that's something we

00:17:09.360 --> 00:17:10.560
wanted to fix for Mac OS X.

00:17:10.680 --> 00:17:15.810
So now in Mac OS X,
all of the services are integrated

00:17:15.810 --> 00:17:15.810
with the core Directory architecture.

00:17:15.880 --> 00:17:18.030
And as you saw, it is extensible.

00:17:18.360 --> 00:17:21.930
It's a runtime plugin architecture,
so you can develop new directory plugins

00:17:22.010 --> 00:17:26.000
that allow applications to access new
directories without having to touch the

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:28.440
code or recompile those applications.

00:17:28.560 --> 00:17:32.470
And we ourselves will be delivering
NetInfo and LDAP support as part

00:17:32.540 --> 00:17:36.660
of the core directory services
in the desktop and on the server.

00:17:37.830 --> 00:17:39.820
On the server side,
in addition to the APIs for

00:17:39.850 --> 00:17:42.400
accessing the directory,
we're also providing the NetInfo

00:17:42.400 --> 00:17:43.610
Directory Service itself.

00:17:43.740 --> 00:17:48.200
This is Apple's distributed
replicated directory service,

00:17:48.200 --> 00:17:52.680
and this provides the ability to
manage users and resources on the

00:17:52.680 --> 00:17:54.880
network for a Mac OS X Server.

00:17:56.460 --> 00:17:59.040
We recognize, again,
that there will be clients

00:17:59.200 --> 00:18:01.830
that don't use NetInfo that
want to access this directory,

00:18:01.980 --> 00:18:06.760
and so we will be providing LDAP server
support as well to provide the same

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:09.900
data in response to LDAP queries.

00:18:10.130 --> 00:18:12.720
In addition,
we know that if we're using an

00:18:12.720 --> 00:18:15.900
external directory such as LDAP,
for instance,

00:18:15.970 --> 00:18:19.940
if you want services in Mac OS X to
be able to take advantage of this,

00:18:20.030 --> 00:18:23.040
we have a standard schema that you
can enter into the LDAP directory

00:18:23.040 --> 00:18:26.180
to allow accounts in Mac OS X to
log in and to utilize services

00:18:26.610 --> 00:18:28.500
through this LDAP directory.

00:18:28.500 --> 00:18:32.200
And so that is all well
defined in the API.

00:18:33.690 --> 00:18:35.620
So where's the opportunities
for you in all this?

00:18:35.790 --> 00:18:38.210
Well, first and foremost,
if you have a directory,

00:18:38.300 --> 00:18:40.830
if you're a systems developer,
or perhaps you're

00:18:40.830 --> 00:18:44.320
working at a university,
you have a proprietary directory,

00:18:44.320 --> 00:18:47.190
in particular to your site,
we want your directory

00:18:47.190 --> 00:18:48.780
to work with Mac OS X.

00:18:48.860 --> 00:18:51.900
So develop a plug-in for your directory.

00:18:51.990 --> 00:18:55.140
And secondly,
if you're developing an application,

00:18:55.260 --> 00:18:58.470
whether it be a productivity
application like email,

00:18:58.640 --> 00:19:00.720
calendars, et cetera,
or a vertical application,

00:19:00.720 --> 00:19:03.570
if you're doing directory access,
you'll want to use the Directory API.

00:19:03.580 --> 00:19:06.140
And finally, of course,
managing directories

00:19:06.140 --> 00:19:09.060
is a complex activity,
and so there is opportunity here

00:19:09.060 --> 00:19:12.730
as well to provide management
utilities for directory services.

