There is an additional session tomorrow
that you'll want to be aware of if you're

00:19:16.820 --> 00:19:20.800
interested in learning more about the
Directory APIs and developing to them,

00:19:20.800 --> 00:19:23.800
and that's going to be in this
room tomorrow at the same time.

00:19:23.800 --> 00:19:27.420
And so if you're interested in this,
please come back tomorrow and hear

00:19:27.420 --> 00:19:30.720
more about the Directory API and
how to develop plug-ins and how to

00:19:30.830 --> 00:19:32.790
use the API for your applications.

00:19:33.650 --> 00:19:37.090
Okay, so the directory, of course,
sits on both the client and the server.

00:19:37.330 --> 00:19:40.890
Now we're going to talk specifically
about some stuff that is part of the

00:19:40.890 --> 00:19:45.470
server and will be in the server version
of the Mac OS X operating system.

00:19:45.470 --> 00:19:48.040
And I'll tell you a little
bit about where we're going

00:19:48.110 --> 00:19:49.790
from a technology standpoint.

00:19:50.090 --> 00:19:56.120
File Services, as Ken mentioned,
is a core staple of a server offering.

00:19:56.250 --> 00:19:59.000
And so with File Services,
we want to provide basic,

00:19:59.090 --> 00:20:03.000
high-performance,
reliable services for any client.

00:20:03.050 --> 00:20:05.290
And in addition,
because Sherlock is a core

00:20:05.420 --> 00:20:08.540
part of Apple's technology,
we want to make sure that the

00:20:08.540 --> 00:20:12.780
indexing support for Sherlock is
built into the File Services as well.

00:20:13.500 --> 00:20:15.260
So again, how does this fit together?

00:20:15.310 --> 00:20:19.660
Well, if you look at this at the top,
you see a variety of file services that

00:20:19.680 --> 00:20:22.320
we want to support in Mac OS X Server.

00:20:22.520 --> 00:20:24.850
And the key here is that
these are all shared.

00:20:24.910 --> 00:20:28.330
A key goal of Mac OS X Server is to
bring all these services together

00:20:28.430 --> 00:20:31.400
and to make the configuration and
the privilege management integrated,

00:20:31.400 --> 00:20:35.040
sitting on top of the Mac OS X operating
system and the Mac OS X file

00:20:35.040 --> 00:20:37.250
system and file system privileges.

00:20:37.400 --> 00:20:40.100
And of course,
all of these services use the

00:20:40.100 --> 00:20:43.790
Directory Service for user
access and authentication.

00:20:44.320 --> 00:20:47.700
So as far as the services themselves,
of course we have AFP.

00:20:47.700 --> 00:20:50.710
And with AFP we've introduced
some changes to the protocol.

00:20:50.820 --> 00:20:53.640
So we have a new version, 3.0,
that adds some more features

00:20:53.790 --> 00:20:57.560
for support of Mac OS X,
the Mac OS X desktop.

00:20:57.610 --> 00:20:59.250
In addition, we have SMB support.

00:20:59.310 --> 00:21:03.160
That's something that is new to the
upcoming version of Mac OS X Server.

00:21:03.220 --> 00:21:05.020
Our SMB support is based on Samba.

00:21:05.120 --> 00:21:06.460
I'm sure a lot of you
are familiar with that.

00:21:06.460 --> 00:21:10.220
It is the best third-party implementation
of Windows File Support around.

00:21:10.300 --> 00:21:12.950
It's open source and
it's been well tested.

00:21:13.040 --> 00:21:15.420
And so that's something that
we are going to be providing

00:21:15.620 --> 00:21:18.370
in Mac OS X Server as well.

00:21:21.620 --> 00:21:26.000
Mac OS X Server is UNIX,
so underneath the hood in Darwin,

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:30.260
there is UNIX down there,
and so there is NFS in there as well.

00:21:30.260 --> 00:21:33.500
So that is additional service that
will be provided for UNIX clients.

00:21:33.510 --> 00:21:36.310
And of course, FTP,
if you have web browsers you want

00:21:36.310 --> 00:21:40.500
to download across the internet,
FTP of course needs to be there as well.

00:21:40.650 --> 00:21:44.570
And one of the shortcomings of the
current version of Mac OS X Server that's

00:21:44.570 --> 00:21:47.790
shipping today is that there are
some limitations in the servers on

00:21:47.790 --> 00:21:49.500
what file systems you can export.

00:21:49.500 --> 00:21:51.430
So we wanted to remove that.

00:21:51.570 --> 00:21:54.220
So services like AFP and SMB in
the future will be able to work

00:21:54.460 --> 00:21:58.500
with the various file services
that come inside of Mac OS X.

00:21:58.520 --> 00:22:02.110
So whether it's HFS or UFS,
etc., you'll be able to manage

00:22:02.110 --> 00:22:06.500
both of those and export both of
those through the various services.

00:22:06.500 --> 00:22:10.400
And of course, as we saw in the picture,
all of it is unified.

00:22:10.550 --> 00:22:14.750
A key part of our overall server offering
is to make it very simple to use and

00:22:14.750 --> 00:22:17.500
unified in terms of the management.

00:22:17.500 --> 00:22:20.120
The performance is something that
we've been working hard at to

00:22:20.250 --> 00:22:21.500
make sure that it is very fast.

00:22:21.500 --> 00:22:24.420
And you've probably seen
some of the demos around SMP,

00:22:24.500 --> 00:22:27.500
and you know we are working hard
to make sure that in the future

00:22:27.500 --> 00:22:30.500
when SMP is available that we'll
be able to take advantage of that.

00:22:30.500 --> 00:22:33.530
And of course,
we leverage the reliability of

00:22:33.530 --> 00:22:35.260
the Mac OS X kernel as well.

00:22:35.670 --> 00:22:37.840
And in addition,
we've put some work into making

00:22:37.840 --> 00:22:40.840
sure that there are watchdog
services and other capabilities

00:22:40.840 --> 00:22:42.710
to keep the server up and running.

00:22:43.860 --> 00:22:46.690
In terms of developer opportunities here,
the first thing you should be

00:22:46.690 --> 00:22:50.440
aware of is that if you're an
AFP developer on any platform,

00:22:50.440 --> 00:22:55.510
you should support AFP 3.0 to
provide full support for Mac OS X.

00:22:55.850 --> 00:22:57.770
Secondly,
if you're doing a directory plugin

00:22:58.050 --> 00:23:02.140
that requires more than just a username
and password for authentication,

00:23:02.140 --> 00:23:05.180
then you'll want to know about
custom user access methods that

00:23:05.180 --> 00:23:07.040
are part of the Apple Share client.

00:23:07.090 --> 00:23:10.380
And this allows you to do
complex authentication dialogues.

00:23:10.440 --> 00:23:12.280
Most cases you won't need this,
but if you're doing

00:23:12.380 --> 00:23:15.020
something really fancy,
it's something you should be aware of.

00:23:15.060 --> 00:23:17.410
And finally,
there are some extension APIs and

00:23:17.410 --> 00:23:20.130
the capability to extend some
of these services that you

00:23:20.130 --> 00:23:23.220
might be interested in as well.

00:23:23.300 --> 00:23:27.370
Print services is the other
staple of a server offering.

00:23:28.820 --> 00:23:31.890
And the key thing to be aware of
about printing on Mac OS X is that

00:23:31.890 --> 00:23:34.500
there's a whole new print architecture.

00:23:34.600 --> 00:23:37.390
And so if you're involved in any
way in printing or print services,

00:23:37.400 --> 00:23:39.440
this is something that you're
going to want to learn a lot about.

00:23:39.540 --> 00:23:41.880
And there's a couple sessions
about that coming up,

00:23:41.980 --> 00:23:44.040
and I'll point you to those in a minute.

00:23:44.240 --> 00:23:48.060
But another thing as far as
printing in Mac OS X Server is that

00:23:48.060 --> 00:23:51.130
we've layered all of our services
on this print architecture.

00:23:51.280 --> 00:23:54.090
So in the past, in Mac OS 9,
we had a completely

00:23:54.090 --> 00:23:56.760
separate print service,
completely separate print

00:23:56.760 --> 00:24:00.070
architecture that couldn't leverage
anything on the server side that

00:24:00.070 --> 00:24:01.380
had been done on the client side.

00:24:01.380 --> 00:24:03.360
And of course, that was a shortcoming,
and we fixed this.

00:24:03.480 --> 00:24:06.670
So now as a developer,
if you have a driver for a

00:24:06.670 --> 00:24:09.830
particular type of printer,
it will work on both the

00:24:09.910 --> 00:24:11.010
server and the desktop.

00:24:11.080 --> 00:24:14.650
So that's something that is good news,
and you should be aware of that.

00:24:14.950 --> 00:24:17.930
In addition,
the printers that we support right now,

00:24:17.980 --> 00:24:20.630
the printing protocols
support PostScript.

00:24:20.820 --> 00:24:23.480
But if you want to do converters,
for instance,

00:24:23.680 --> 00:24:27.110
that would take you to a raster printer
on the back end for the desktop.

00:24:27.210 --> 00:24:29.750
That will also work on the server.

00:24:31.010 --> 00:24:31.680
So printing.

00:24:31.870 --> 00:24:36.170
So we support clients, both Macintosh,
Windows, and Unix.

00:24:36.290 --> 00:24:38.080
Again,
the Windows support comes from Samba,

00:24:38.270 --> 00:24:40.280
so we get very robust support there.

00:24:40.340 --> 00:24:43.420
And the support for the queues,
of course, right now is any

00:24:43.420 --> 00:24:44.930
Mac OS X PostScript printer.

00:24:45.220 --> 00:24:47.600
But again, as a developer,
you have the opportunity to put in

00:24:47.600 --> 00:24:51.380
PostScript to raster converters and
have those work on the server as well.

00:24:51.430 --> 00:24:54.350
And of course, because it's a server,
you can manage the queues and manage

00:24:54.350 --> 00:25:00.010
the print jobs over the network as part
of our integrated management utilities.

00:25:00.330 --> 00:25:03.700
As far as print opportunities
for you as a developer,

00:25:03.700 --> 00:25:06.150
first and foremost,
if you have a solution for

00:25:06.150 --> 00:25:10.440
publishing that runs on Unix,
you should port it to Mac OS X.

00:25:10.570 --> 00:25:15.320
So if you're doing print services,
publishing workflow, reps, what have you,

00:25:15.420 --> 00:25:16.500
there is an opportunity here.

00:25:16.500 --> 00:25:18.540
It's very easy to port
these services to X,

00:25:18.620 --> 00:25:20.060
and you should get started.

00:25:20.240 --> 00:25:22.890
And I know some people already
have products running here,

00:25:22.890 --> 00:25:24.890
but if you don't,
it's time to get started.

00:25:25.140 --> 00:25:27.820
And the other thing here,
which I mentioned,

00:25:27.820 --> 00:25:32.440
is that drivers for the client
side will also work for the server.

00:25:32.540 --> 00:25:36.060
So it makes it very easy to support
additional types of printers on the

00:25:36.080 --> 00:25:38.260
server side as well as the desktop.

00:25:38.340 --> 00:25:40.820
And of course,
there is also the opportunity to

00:25:40.870 --> 00:25:44.610
add additional management tools
to our server products as well.

00:25:45.710 --> 00:25:47.830
Okay, so that covers File and Print.

00:25:47.920 --> 00:25:51.630
Now another key area of our service
offering is Internet Services.

00:25:51.630 --> 00:25:54.810
And Internet Services, of course,
any core piece of any server

00:25:54.810 --> 00:25:56.350
is web and email services.

00:25:56.510 --> 00:25:58.530
But we also have two
technology areas that are very

00:25:58.530 --> 00:26:01.290
important to us here at Apple,
and that's QuickTime and WebObjects.

00:26:01.400 --> 00:26:06.140
And you've probably heard a lot about
those at the conference here so far.

00:26:06.760 --> 00:26:09.060
On the web side,
of course we want to have a web

00:26:09.060 --> 00:26:13.200
service that provides web site hosting,
whether it be very simple,

00:26:13.200 --> 00:26:15.450
something you want to get
up and running in minutes,

00:26:15.450 --> 00:26:18.710
to very sophisticated
sites with virtual hosts.

00:26:18.860 --> 00:26:22.940
A service that has a full-featured
web server with high performance.

00:26:22.990 --> 00:26:27.080
And of course we need it to be
integrated with our management solution,

00:26:27.080 --> 00:26:30.160
and we need it to be able to support
application development services like

00:26:30.160 --> 00:26:33.130
WebObjects or like server-side scripting.

00:26:33.980 --> 00:26:36.120
And the way we do this, of course,
is with standard Apache.

00:26:36.120 --> 00:26:38.800
Those of you who are familiar with
the current Mac OS X Server know

00:26:38.800 --> 00:26:40.810
that it includes standard Apache.

00:26:41.020 --> 00:26:42.660
It is the standard Apache module.

00:26:42.660 --> 00:26:44.710
In fact,
if you took the open source Apache and

00:26:44.710 --> 00:26:47.360
recompiled it and substituted it in,
it would work just fine.

00:26:47.360 --> 00:26:52.160
So this is fully standard
Apache with the dynamic module API.

00:26:52.240 --> 00:26:54.590
And to that,
we've added server-side scripting.

00:26:54.640 --> 00:26:58.980
It's available through
standard Apache modules.

00:26:59.470 --> 00:27:01.120
Apache is well used
throughout the internet.

00:27:01.250 --> 00:27:03.640
There's almost 9 million
sites using Apache now.

00:27:03.640 --> 00:27:06.250
It's about 60% of the internet.

00:27:06.340 --> 00:27:08.150
But even though it's well used,
it's not the highest

00:27:08.150 --> 00:27:09.340
performing server out there.

00:27:09.340 --> 00:27:11.870
And so we've put a lot of work
into increasing the performance.

00:27:11.940 --> 00:27:15.510
And so that's an area where we're
going to continue to work on to have

00:27:15.510 --> 00:27:17.660
a really high performance product.

00:27:17.740 --> 00:27:20.880
And in addition,
some additional things that are coming in

00:27:20.880 --> 00:27:25.190
the product that we're looking into are,
of course, increasing the capabilities

00:27:25.210 --> 00:27:31.390
as far as SSL and e-commerce,
and also Sherlock indexing for the sites.

00:27:32.200 --> 00:27:34.740
As a developer, of course,
because it is standard Apache,

00:27:34.740 --> 00:27:38.060
it's very easy for you to come
in and develop Apache modules

00:27:38.280 --> 00:27:40.840
to enhance the server,
to add new capabilities,

00:27:40.950 --> 00:27:43.690
or to bring modules onto
the Mac OS X platform.

00:27:43.790 --> 00:27:45.520
And of course,
the opportunity for management

00:27:45.670 --> 00:27:46.600
tools exists as well.

00:27:46.600 --> 00:27:50.080
That's something that's very
important in website management.

00:27:50.860 --> 00:27:53.670
The other area that we're looking
at as far as core web services,

00:27:53.740 --> 00:27:56.330
obviously, is email services.

00:27:57.250 --> 00:27:59.480
They're very widely
used and very important.

00:27:59.530 --> 00:28:03.770
And of course, as part of Mac OS X,
it needs to include an integrated

00:28:03.930 --> 00:28:06.020
and very easy to use email server.

00:28:06.060 --> 00:28:10.880
And of course, it needs to scale as well
and be high performance.

00:28:10.920 --> 00:28:13.820
And because we have a lot of customers
that run on sites that have intermittent

00:28:13.820 --> 00:28:15.920
connections to the internet,
we need to be able to support

00:28:15.920 --> 00:28:20.200
message delivery remotely as well
through intermittent connections.

00:28:20.200 --> 00:28:24.100
And the way we do this, of course,
is that we will be providing an

00:28:24.100 --> 00:28:30.140
integrated mail server that includes
SMTP for message delivery and routing,

00:28:30.190 --> 00:28:33.340
as well as POP and IMAP mailbox services.

00:28:33.400 --> 00:28:36.350
Now, this server will work completely
by itself independently,

00:28:36.360 --> 00:28:39.440
but because there are a lot of
folks that want to do more advanced

00:28:39.440 --> 00:28:42.760
scripting of mail delivery and routing,
we have the option to work

00:28:42.760 --> 00:28:44.940
with SendMail for delivery.

00:28:44.990 --> 00:28:47.890
Or for that matter,
any other mail delivery

00:28:47.890 --> 00:28:51.400
agent can be configured to
do the mail routing as well.

00:28:51.440 --> 00:28:53.300
And of course,
like any mail server these days,

00:28:53.300 --> 00:28:57.580
it includes anti-spam and the
message delivery capabilities

00:28:57.630 --> 00:28:59.150
that we talked about.

00:29:00.170 --> 00:29:02.850
Another part of our mail server is that
it's integrated with the directory.

00:29:02.870 --> 00:29:05.420
So whether you're using our own
directory or whether you're using LDAP,

00:29:05.530 --> 00:29:09.390
you can code into the directory
where the user's mailbox is

00:29:09.390 --> 00:29:11.310
located and what machine it's on.

00:29:11.310 --> 00:29:15.800
And routing can be set up for complex
mail installations in that manner.

00:29:15.880 --> 00:29:18.440
And finally,
we have something that exists today in

00:29:18.440 --> 00:29:23.020
Apple Share IP which we'll carry forward,
and that's our IMAP administration port,

00:29:23.020 --> 00:29:25.520
which for people wanting to do
additional management utilities

00:29:25.610 --> 00:29:28.430
makes it very easy to go in
through IMAP with an administrator

00:29:28.430 --> 00:29:30.100
account and have full access.

00:29:30.110 --> 00:29:34.270
So the entire mail store,
all the accounts and all the messages for

00:29:34.270 --> 00:29:37.090
management reporting and what have you.

00:29:38.060 --> 00:29:41.500
So in terms of developer opportunities,
well, there's two sides here.

00:29:41.500 --> 00:29:44.760
One is if you have an application,
for instance, a server-side application,

00:29:44.840 --> 00:29:49.300
say web-based email as an example,
make sure it runs on 10.

00:29:49.340 --> 00:29:51.860
The other is if you have
a client application,

00:29:51.860 --> 00:29:55.900
make sure it runs well in markets
that are important to Mac customers.

00:29:55.950 --> 00:29:59.760
A good example here is the K-12
market where the mail users don't

00:29:59.760 --> 00:30:03.700
have ownership of a particular
machine and need to move from machine

00:30:03.700 --> 00:30:05.600
to machine to access their mail.

00:30:05.630 --> 00:30:07.980
On the management side, of course,
there are a variety of management

00:30:08.120 --> 00:30:10.040
tools that can be built,
including account

00:30:10.040 --> 00:30:14.100
management through IMAP,
management of routing through SendMail,

00:30:14.190 --> 00:30:18.190
as well as log management
or mail tracking.

00:30:19.340 --> 00:30:23.660
So let's move on to two of the services
that are core to us here at Apple.

00:30:23.660 --> 00:30:26.640
First one is QuickTime and
QuickTime Streaming Server.

00:30:26.710 --> 00:30:29.530
Now, QuickTime Streaming Server,
hopefully most of you have heard of this,

00:30:29.610 --> 00:30:35.430
but in case you haven't,
it delivers live media or on-demand

00:30:35.430 --> 00:30:38.490
media through QuickTime movies
across the internet to hundreds

00:30:38.530 --> 00:30:39.600
or thousands of customers.

00:30:39.740 --> 00:30:42.600
So you can take an application
that's broadcasting live media,

00:30:42.600 --> 00:30:46.770
say a radio show or a video, live video,
and basically have the

00:30:46.770 --> 00:30:50.180
QuickTime Streaming Server deliver
that to hundreds of customers,

00:30:50.270 --> 00:30:51.500
thousands of customers.

00:30:51.650 --> 00:30:55.100
Or you can take a QuickTime movie and
hint it and put it up on the server,

00:30:55.190 --> 00:30:58.840
and that movie can be accessed
on-demand and streamed to customers.

00:30:58.950 --> 00:31:00.250
It's completely standards-based.

00:31:00.480 --> 00:31:05.500
It runs on the RTSP and
RTP IETF protocols,

00:31:05.600 --> 00:31:09.630
so it is the only fully standards-based
streaming solution out there.

00:31:09.740 --> 00:31:14.150
And in addition to being a server,
you can also relay other broadcasts.

00:31:14.260 --> 00:31:17.610
So basically you can set up--
. a relay of a live broadcast,

00:31:17.610 --> 00:31:21.910
or you can set up multiple relays to
scale up a very large configuration for

00:31:21.910 --> 00:31:25.540
thousands and thousands of customers.

00:31:25.700 --> 00:31:29.160
Each server itself is highly scalable,
so whether you want to support a 56k

00:31:29.290 --> 00:31:34.660
modem or a 288 modem or go to broadband,
DSL, or cable, or even to Internet at

00:31:34.660 --> 00:31:37.420
megabits per second,
the server is capable of handling that.

00:31:37.630 --> 00:31:40.560
And at modem speeds it can
handle thousands of connections.

00:31:40.560 --> 00:31:43.760
And the other thing it's capable
of doing that's important is

00:31:43.890 --> 00:31:47.560
usually over the Internet most
connections are done unicast.

00:31:47.560 --> 00:31:50.560
You take a connection from the server
and you send data to the client,

00:31:50.560 --> 00:31:52.560
and that's a single connection,
a single pipe.

00:31:52.560 --> 00:31:55.480
So if you have thousands of clients,
you have thousands of connections.

00:31:55.560 --> 00:31:58.520
But the server itself is also
capable of handling multicast.

00:31:58.610 --> 00:32:01.560
So if you're in an area of the
Internet that can handle multicast,

00:32:01.650 --> 00:32:03.560
or if you're on an intranet
where it's configured,

00:32:03.580 --> 00:32:08.510
you have the ability to reach a lot more
clients with less network bandwidth.

00:32:09.630 --> 00:32:12.100
The server itself also
has web administration,

00:32:12.100 --> 00:32:13.700
something that we've been working on.

00:32:13.790 --> 00:32:16.300
And of course,
if you haven't heard of it,

00:32:16.300 --> 00:32:20.100
hopefully you'll want to check it
out because it's fully open source.

00:32:20.280 --> 00:32:24.610
Some of our competitors will charge
about $50,000 for a product like this,

00:32:24.770 --> 00:32:25.870
but for us it's free.

00:32:26.040 --> 00:32:29.700
And so you can go out and get the server,
you can get the source today,

00:32:29.870 --> 00:32:30.300
check it out.

00:32:30.300 --> 00:32:34.050
It runs on multiple platforms
in addition to Mac OS X Server.

00:32:34.170 --> 00:32:38.570
And so this is what we think is the
most expandable streaming server around.

00:32:38.710 --> 00:32:40.820
Not only is it open source,
you have full access to the

00:32:40.820 --> 00:32:43.700
source to do whatever you want,
but it also has a module API,

00:32:43.700 --> 00:32:44.870
similar to Apache.

00:32:45.020 --> 00:32:48.070
So different developers can come
up and add new functions to the

00:32:48.160 --> 00:32:51.940
server without having to learn
the whole source base or without

00:32:52.020 --> 00:32:54.070
having to get in each other's way.

00:32:54.100 --> 00:32:58.000
And this is important for you
as a developer as an opportunity

00:32:58.000 --> 00:33:02.100
because it allows you to develop
new features to the server.

00:33:02.100 --> 00:33:04.090
The streaming market
is expanding rapidly.

00:33:04.090 --> 00:33:05.720
It's a very rapidly growing market.

00:33:05.720 --> 00:33:08.400
And there's a real opportunity to
get in here and add new features.

00:33:08.400 --> 00:33:11.530
But it allows you to add those new
features not only as open source,

00:33:11.590 --> 00:33:15.100
but also as modules which can be
shipped independently of the server.

00:33:15.100 --> 00:33:18.300
And you can sell those modules as
binaries and sell them for money.

00:33:18.300 --> 00:33:21.970
So there's an opportunity to go
both ways here and certainly a

00:33:21.970 --> 00:33:24.700
good developer opportunity in
building modules for the server.

00:33:24.700 --> 00:33:27.330
